  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Properties with granny flats, or what is increasingly referred to as secondary dwellings, attract genuine and motivated buyers across Brisbane's inner east. Multigenerational families want them for ageing parents or adult children. Investors see an income-producing asset in a suburb where freestanding houses command strong prices. Buyers who want to offset mortgage costs with rental income are a growing group, particularly as inner-city rents have remained firm. The challenge for sellers is that marketing and valuing dual-living properties requires a different approach to a standard campaign, and getting the approach wrong can mean leaving real money on the table or, worse, making representations that are legally problematic.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How granny flats are valued in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Valuers assess properties with secondary dwellings using two broad approaches, and which one dominates depends on the buyer profile likely to purchase the property and what comparable sales evidence exists.</p>

      <p>The capital approach looks at what similar dual-living properties in the same suburb have sold for, and assesses the premium a secondary dwelling adds to the land and main residence value. This method works well in suburbs where there is reasonable transaction volume in dual-living properties, allowing valuers to draw direct comparisons. In Brisbane's inner east, suburbs like Cannon Hill, Coorparoo, and Tingalpa have seen enough dual-living sales to support this kind of analysis.</p>

      <p>The income approach is more commonly applied when the secondary dwelling is self-contained, separately accessible, and consistently tenanted. The valuer capitalises the rental income from the granny flat at a market yield to arrive at a contributed value, then adds this to the assessed value of the main residence. The challenge with the income approach is that valuers tend to be conservative with the yields they apply, and the resulting valuation can sometimes be lower than what the market actually pays for the income stream.</p>

      <p>In practice, a well-positioned dual-living property in Brisbane's inner east will often achieve a price at auction that exceeds the formal valuation, particularly if the campaign attracts both multigenerational buyers and investors bidding competitively. The dual buyer pool is the asset: you are not relying solely on owner-occupiers, which broadens genuine competition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Council approval and what happens with unapproved structures</h2>
      <p>Before you list, your agent will need to know whether the granny flat has development approval from Brisbane City Council. This matters significantly for two reasons: disclosure obligations and buyer financing.</p>

      <p>In Queensland, a material fact is anything a buyer would reasonably consider relevant to their decision to purchase. An unapproved structure is a material fact that must be disclosed. Failure to disclose it can expose a seller to a compensation claim or, in serious cases, allow a buyer to rescind the contract. Your solicitor will advise you on how to structure the disclosure in the contract, but the disclosure must be made.</p>

      <p>On the financing side, many lenders will not include the rental income from an unapproved dwelling in their serviceability assessment. Some will decline to lend against the property at all if the secondary dwelling is prominent and unapproved, as they view it as a liability rather than an asset. This restricts your buyer pool to cash buyers or buyers whose lender takes a more pragmatic approach, which reduces competition and can affect price. If you have an unapproved granny flat and time to address it before listing, getting the structure assessed for potential approval, or at minimum understanding what approving or removing it would involve, is worthwhile.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The buyer profiles attracted to dual-living properties</h2>
      <p>Understanding who will actually buy your property is the foundation of a good campaign strategy.</p>

      <p>Multigenerational family buyers want privacy and proximity for parents or adult children. They look for separate entrances, self-contained amenities, and layouts that allow genuine independence within the same property. For this buyer, the granny flat is not an investment decision but a practical and emotional one, and they often pay a premium over comparable properties without secondary dwellings because the alternative is buying a second home entirely. In Brisbane's inner east, where house prices are strong and good schools are a genuine driver of buyer demand, multigenerational buyers are a consistent presence in dual-living campaigns.</p>

      <p>Investor buyers are motivated by yield, approval status, and the prospect of capital growth in a high-demand suburb. They will want to know the realistic rental income for both dwellings, the vacancy rates in the suburb, and whether the granny flat is separately metered and separately accessible. They are typically more rigorous in their due diligence than owner-occupier buyers, and they will test any income claims you make against current market rents for comparable properties.</p>

      <p>The mortgage-offset buyer sits between these groups: an owner-occupier who intends to live in the main house and rent the granny flat to reduce their holding costs. This buyer is often more stretched financially than a pure investor and is sensitive to yield, but is also motivated by lifestyle factors like suburb, school catchment, and street. They are a significant part of the dual-living buyer pool in inner-east Brisbane and are often the most competitive bidders at auction precisely because they are buying a home as well as an income stream.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Inner east Brisbane suburbs where granny flats add the most value</h2>
      <p>The value a granny flat adds depends partly on what land it sits on and partly on the buyer demand in that suburb. In suburbs where land values are already high, a granny flat adds a relatively lower percentage premium but a higher absolute dollar value. In suburbs where land is more affordable but rental demand is strong, the income return from the secondary dwelling can be the primary driver of value.</p>

      <p>In the inner east, suburbs like Cannon Hill, Coorparoo, Camp Hill, and Tingalpa have strong buyer demand for dual-living properties from all three buyer profiles described above. The combination of good school catchments, access to arterial roads, and genuine land size means there is real competition for well-presented dual-living properties when they are marketed properly. Suburbs like Bulimba and Hawthorne attract more multigenerational and high-income buyer profiles, where the income story is secondary to the lifestyle and land quality story.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What you can legally say in marketing about rental income</h2>
      <p>This is the area where sellers most commonly make expensive mistakes. Making specific rental income claims in marketing materials, whether in the listing headline, the property description, or verbally at open homes, carries legal risk if those claims are not accurate or cannot be substantiated.</p>

      <p>Under Queensland's Property Occupations Act 2014, agents and sellers must not engage in conduct that is misleading or deceptive in connection with a property transaction. Stating that the granny flat "rents for $X per week" when it is currently vacant, or quoting a rental income that is above current market rents for the property type, can expose both agent and seller to a complaint and potential compensation claim.</p>

      <p>What can be said legitimately: current lease terms and rent if the property is tenanted, a market rent estimate from a licensed property manager based on comparable current rentals, and factual information about the dwelling's size, facilities, and approval status. The phrase "potential rental income" is acceptable when accompanied by context, but should be grounded in a formal estimate rather than an aspirational figure invented for marketing purposes.</p>

      <p>If the granny flat is currently tenanted, provide the current lease to your agent. If it is vacant, obtain a rental appraisal from a property management company familiar with the suburb before the campaign launches. This gives you a defensible figure and a document you can attach to the contract or make available to buyers who request it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting dual-living properties for maximum buyer appeal</h2>
      <p>The presentation of a dual-living property requires thinking about two separate buyer experiences simultaneously. The main residence needs to present to the same standard as any comparable property in the suburb: decluttered, freshly presented, professionally photographed. But the granny flat needs its own camera run, its own presentation, and its own position in the marketing narrative.</p>

      <p>Buyers attending open homes for dual-living properties often want to inspect both dwellings independently. Where possible, arrange the inspection so buyers can enter the granny flat via its own entrance, not through the main house. This reinforces the independence of the dwelling and makes the dual-living proposition feel genuine rather than just a talking point in the listing. Poorly presented granny flats, or those that require significant work before they could be tenanted, actively undermine the value proposition to investor and mortgage-offset buyers.</p>

      <p>A floorplan that shows both dwellings clearly, with measurements, is a genuine conversion tool for dual-living buyers who are trying to understand the practical layout before they inspect. Including the total combined floor area as well as each dwelling separately gives buyers the information they need to make a confident decision to inspect, which is the first and most important step in a strong campaign result.</p>

